          "body": "The arrival of Abiathar with the ephod (23:6) is not an incidental detail. The last named priestly oracle before this chapter was Ahimelech's aid to David in chapter 21, which Saul punished with the massacre of 85 priests (22:17-19). Saul has effectively severed the formal channel of priestly inquiry from himself — and it has landed with the fugitive he is hunting. When David discovers Saul's plan (23:9), he does not attempt political maneuvering or armed resistance; he brings the ephod. The oracle he receives is remarkable: God answers counterfactual questions (23:11-12). 'Will Saul come down?' — yes. 'Will the Keilahites surrender me?' — yes. These are conditional futures, events that will not happen if David departs. The God of Israel is not limited to commenting on what has occurred; He speaks to what would occur under different conditions. This is not merely tactical; it is a theological statement about divine omniscience that Calvin and later Reformed theologians would use in their treatment of God's knowledge of counterfactuals (cf. the Westminster Confession on God's foreknowledge). David acts on the oracle, departs with 600 men, and Saul abandons his siege before it begins."
