        "excerpt": "Then David said, 'Will the men of Keilah surrender me and my men into the hand of Saul?' And the LORD said, 'They will surrender you.'",
        "body": "The Keilah episode (vv. 6-13) is one of the most theologically precise oracular scenes in the Old Testament. Abiathar's arrival with the ephod (v. 6) creates the narrative possibility for formal inquiry; it also signals the transfer of legitimate priestly access from Saul to David. Saul had massacred the Nob priests (22:17-18) and thereby severed himself from the very channel through which God had communicated with Israel's leadership. The ephod — the material instrument of priestly inquiry — now travels with the fugitive, not the king.\n\nSaul's theological misreading in verse 7 deserves careful attention. He interprets David's entry into a walled city as divine deliverance: 'God has delivered him into my hand.' This is a genuine attempt to read providence — and it is completely wrong. Saul is reading circumstances as confirmation of his own will rather than as God's disclosure. The chapter's central irony is that Saul believes God is working with him at precisely the moments God is working against him. John Calvin (Institutes I.17.1) notes that Providence is not self-interpreting; the wicked read their momentary advantages as divine sanction and are deceived.\n\nThe oracle of verses 11-12 is extraordinary in scope. David asks two questions: Will Saul come down? Will the Keilahites surrender me? Both questions concern future contingencies — not what has happened, not what is currently happening, but what would happen under two different scenarios. The LORD answers both directly: yes, Saul will come down; yes, the Keilahites will surrender you. This constitutes a divine declaration of counterfactual knowledge — God knows not only what will happen but what would happen under conditions that will never obtain, because David's departure will prevent Saul's arrival. Reformed theology has named this 'middle knowledge' or scientia media (cf. Luis de Molina; affirmed also in the Westminster Confession's teaching on God's foreknowledge of all possible events). The narrative is not interested in the philosophical category, but it grounds David's decision in something more reliable than political calculation: a God who knows what would happen tells him what to do before it happens.\n\nDavid's response is notable for its restraint: he does not punish the Keilahites for their hypothetical treachery, does not issue a public condemnation, and does not attempt to use them as human shields. He simply departs with 600 men. The text measures his character by what he does not do.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Sagar* (deliver/surrender, vv. 7, 11, 12) means to shut up or enclose — used of closing a city gate and of handing a prisoner over. The word Saul uses in v. 7 ('he has trapped himself') and the word used of what the Keilahites would do (vv. 11, 12) are the same root. The city David saved would have become the enclosure that destroyed him."
