        "excerpt": "And Jonathan, Saul's son, arose and went to David at Horesh, and encouraged him in God.",
        "body": "Verse 14 contains the chapter's central theological assertion embedded in a narrative summary: 'Saul sought him every day, but God did not deliver him into his hand.' This is not incidental narrator comment; it is the interpretive key to everything in the chapter. The daily nature of Saul's pursuit (yom, distributive — day after day) and God's daily withholding are placed in direct contrast. What kept David alive was not superior tactics, better terrain, or Jonathan's loyalty. It was God's active restraint of Saul's hand.\n\nThe Jonathan scene (vv. 16-18) is the human face of that divine protection. Jonathan 'arose and went' — the text emphasizes initiative and movement; no one sent for him, no message came from David. He makes the dangerous journey into the wilderness to find a fugitive. His ministry is described with striking precision: he 'strengthened his hand in God' (*chazaq et yado be-Elohim*). The idiom chazaq yad appears throughout the Old Testament for the strengthening of a person's grip or resolve (Judges 9:24; Ezra 1:6; Nehemiah 2:18). Here, critically, the strengthening is in God — Jonathan does not strengthen David's confidence in Jonathan, or in their covenant, or in Judah's eventual loyalty. He reinforces David's reliance on the God who is already withholding Saul.\n\nJonathan's three-part oracle (v. 17) is the chapter's most explicit theological statement: (1) Saul will not find you; (2) you will be king over Israel; (3) I will be next to you. The second statement is the anointing promise of 1 Samuel 16 spoken back to David at his lowest point. The third statement is more remarkable still: Jonathan, the natural heir, voluntarily places himself in the subordinate position with no trace of resentment. This is what Tim Keller (The Reason for God, 2008) would call a picture of the self-giving love that runs through the canonical grain — Jonathan losing so that the covenant purposes of God can advance.\n\nThe covenant of verse 18 is the third recorded covenant between them (1 Samuel 18:3; 20:16-17). Made 'before the LORD' in the wilderness, it is the covenant David will honor in 2 Samuel 9 by seeking Mephibosheth. The scene ends with Jonathan going home — he returns to his father's house, to the dangerous political world of Gibeah. He does not stay with David. The encouragement has been given; the covenant has been made; Jonathan exits. David stays at Horesh, not clinging to the human comfort.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chazaq* (strengthen, v. 16) is the verb of the divine commissioning formula in Joshua 1:6-9 ('be strong and courageous') — Jonathan performs, humanly, what God does theologically. *Berit* (covenant, v. 18) plus *karat* (cut) is the standard Hebrew covenant-making formula; covenants were 'cut' because animals were typically divided in their ratification (cf. Genesis 15:10, 17-18)."
